  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Benson Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "Psalm 44:19-21",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Psalm 44:19-21",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Thou hast sore broken us in the place of dragons — ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "By inflicting upon us one breach after another, thou hast at last brought us to this pass; that we are become like a place extremely desolate, such as dragons love, (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Isaiah 13:21-22",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ",) and therefore full of horror and danger; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "and covered us with the shadow of death — ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "With deadly horrors and miseries. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "If we have forgotten the name of God ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "— That is, God himself, or his worship and service; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "or stretched out our hands to strange gods — ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "In the way of prayer or adoration. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Shall not God search this out?",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " — We appeal to the heart-searching God, concerning the sincerity of this our profession.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Matthew Henry's Concise Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "44:17-26 In afflictions, we must not seek relief by any sinful compliance; but should continually meditate on the truth, purity, and knowledge of our heart-searching God. Hearts sins and secret sins are known to God, and must be reckoned for. He knows the secret of the heart, therefore judges of the words and actions. While our troubles do not drive us from our duty to God, we should not suffer them to drive us from our comfort in God. Let us take care that prosperity and ease do not render us careless and lukewarm. The church of God cannot be prevailed on by persecution to forget God; the believer's heart does not turn back from God. The Spirit of prophecy had reference to those who suffered unto death, for the testimony of Christ. Observe the pleas used, ver. 25,26. Not their own merit and righteousness, but the poor sinner's pleas. None that belong to Christ shall be cast off, but every one of them shall be saved, and that for ever. The mercy of God, purchased, promised, and constantly flowing forth, and offered to believers, does away every doubt arising from our sins; while we pray in faith, Redeem us for thy mercies' sake.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Barnes' Notes on the Bible",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Though thou hast sore broken us in the place of dragons - Or rather, \"That thou hast crushed us in the place of dragons.\" The connection is continued from the previous verse: \"Our heart is not so turned back, nor have our steps so declined from thy path, that thou shouldst crush us in the place of dragons.\" That is, we have been guilty of no such apostasy and infidelity as to account for the fact that thou hast dealt with us in this manner, or make it necessary and proper that we should thus be crushed and overthrown The word rendered \"dragons\" - תנין  tannı̂yn - means either a great fish; a sea monster; a serpent; a dragon; or a crocodile. See the notes at ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Isaiah 13:22",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". It may also mean a jackal, a fox, or a wolf. DeWette renders it here, jackals. The idea in the passage is essentially the same, whichever interpretation of the word is adopted. The \"place of dragons\" would denote the place where such monsters are found, or where they had their abode; that is to say, in desolate places; wastes; deserts; old ruins; depopulated towns. See the notes, as above, at ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Isaiah 13:19-22",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; compare ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Jeremiah 9:11",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". The meaning here would be, therefore, that they had been vanquished; that their cities and towns had been reduced to ruins; that their land had been laid waste; that the place where they had been \"sore broken\" was in fact a fit abode for wild beasts and monsters.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "And covered us with the shadow of death - Our land has been covered with a dark and dismal shade, as if Death had cast his image or shadow over it. See Job 3:5, note; and Psalm 23:4, note. There could be no more striking illustration of calamity and ruin. ",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "And covered us with the shadow of death - Our land has been covered with a dark and dismal shade, as if Death had cast his image or shadow over it. See ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Job 3:5",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": ", note; and ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Psalm 23:4",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": ", note. There could be no more striking illustration of calamity and ruin. ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
  },
