  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Keil and Delitzsch Biblical Commentary on the Old Testament",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "(Heb.: 44:18-22) If Israel compares its conduct towards God with this its lot, it cannot possibly regard it as a punishment that it has justly incurred. Construed with the accusative, בּוא signifies, as in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Psalm 35:8",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Psalm 36:12",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", to come upon one, and more especially of an evil lot and of powers that are hostile. שׁקּר, to lie or deceive, with בּ of the object on whom the deception or treachery is practised, as in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Psalm 89:34",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". In ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Psalm 44:19",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " אשּׁוּר is construed as fem., exactly as in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Job 31:8",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; the fut. consec. is also intended as such (as e.g., in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Job 3:10",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Numbers 16:14",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "): that our step should have declined from, etc.; inward apostasy is followed by outward wandering and downfall. This is therefore not one of the many instances in which the לא of one clause also has influence over the clause that follows (Ges. 152, 3). כּי, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Psalm 44:20",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", has the sense of quod: we have not revolted against Thee, that Thou shouldest on that account have done to us the thing which is now befallen us. Concerning תּנּיּם vid., ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Isaiah 13:22",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". A \"place of jackals\" is, like a habitation of dragons (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Jeremiah 10:22",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), the most lonesome and terrible wilderness; the place chosen was, according to this, an inhospitable מדבר, far removed from the dwellings of men. כּסּה is construed with על of the person covered, and with בּ of that with which (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Samuel 19:13",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") he is covered: Thou coveredst us over with deepest darkness (vid., ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Psalm 23:4",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). אם, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Psalm 44:21",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", is not that of asseveration (verily we have not forgotten), but, as the interrogatory apodosis ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Psalm 44:22",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " shows, conditional: if we have ( equals  should have) forgotten. This would not remain hidden from Him who knoweth the heart, for the secrets of men's hearts are known to Him. Both the form and matter here again strongly remind one of ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Job 31",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", more especially ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Job 31:4",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; cf. also on תּעלמות, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
